Approach 2: HashMap + Slope (Optimal)
Intuition

Fix one point.

Calculate the slope with every other point.

If multiple points have the same slope with the fixed point, they all lie on the same line.

Store

Slope → Frequency

The answer is

Maximum Frequency + 1

(the fixed point itself)

Why use GCD?

Instead of storing

dy/dx

store

dy/gcd
dx/gcd

This avoids precision errors.

Example

2/4

and

1/2

Both become

1/2

Java
class Solution {

    public int maxPoints(int[][] points) {

        if (points.length <= 2)
            return points.length;

        int ans = 2;

        for (int i = 0; i < points.length; i++) {

            HashMap<String, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();

            for (int j = i + 1; j < points.length; j++) {

                int dx = points[j][0] - points[i][0];
                int dy = points[j][1] - points[i][1];

                int gcd = gcd(dx, dy);

                dx /= gcd;
                dy /= gcd;

                String slope = dx + "#" + dy;

                map.put(slope, map.getOrDefault(slope, 0) + 1);

                ans = Math.max(ans, map.get(slope) + 1);
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }

    private int gcd(int a, int b) {

        if (b == 0)
            return Math.abs(a);

        return gcd(b, a % b);
    }
}
